1
00:00:10,219 --> 00:00:12,221
WOMAN: No! Just back off!

2
00:00:12,304 --> 00:00:13,597
(GRUNTS)

3
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:14,973
MAN 1: Come on!

4
00:00:15,057 --> 00:00:17,809
You're going to regret this.
Completely ridiculous!

5
00:00:17,935 --> 00:00:19,853
Get your hand off me.

6
00:00:20,062 --> 00:00:21,313
(GRUNTS)

7
00:00:22,356 --> 00:00:26,401
I think that makes my answer clear.
Don't you?

8
00:00:26,777 --> 00:00:28,278
Oh, and, uh...

9
00:00:28,403 --> 00:00:30,781
If you're going to go to print,
spell my name right.

10
00:00:30,906 --> 00:00:32,783
Rattigan, with two Ts.

11
00:00:33,659 --> 00:00:38,247
Oh, this goes way beyond the newspapers.
This thing's worldwide.

12
00:00:38,330 --> 00:00:40,541
I'm telling you, Atmos is dangerous.

13
00:00:40,624 --> 00:00:43,418
But if you had proof,
then you wouldn't be here.

14
00:00:43,502 --> 00:00:44,670
Fine.

15
00:00:45,087 --> 00:00:48,215
If you won't listen,
I'll find someone else who will.

16
00:00:54,930 --> 00:00:57,808
ATMOS: Welcome.
What is your destination?

17
00:00:58,016 --> 00:01:00,269
You're the last thing I need.

18
00:01:00,519 --> 00:01:02,396
Atmos cannot be disabled.

19
00:01:02,479 --> 00:01:03,647
(GRUNTS)

20
00:01:03,730 --> 00:01:04,815
Right then.

21
00:01:04,898 --> 00:01:08,151
Take me to UNIT headquarters,
Tower Bridge, London.

22
00:01:08,277 --> 00:01:09,486
UNIT headquarters.

23
00:01:09,570 --> 00:01:14,491
Her name's Jo Nakashima,
a freelance journalist.

24
00:01:14,616 --> 00:01:16,743
Clever by the sound of it,
not as clever as me,

25
00:01:16,827 --> 00:01:19,162
but that goes without saying.

26
00:01:19,246 --> 00:01:22,291
I'd recommend termination.

27
00:01:22,374 --> 00:01:26,920
ATMOS: Remember your status, boy.
We do not take orders from humans.

28
00:01:27,004 --> 00:01:29,590
I said, "Recommend".

29
00:01:29,881 --> 00:01:34,511
Then your advice shows military wisdom.
She will be terminated.

30
00:01:37,431 --> 00:01:38,557
Cool.

31
00:01:39,933 --> 00:01:41,768
RECORDED VOICE:
This is UNIT, extension 2217...

32
00:01:41,852 --> 00:01:43,937
Don't put me through to answerphone.

33
00:01:44,021 --> 00:01:45,063
(BEEP)

34
00:01:45,188 --> 00:01:49,234
Yes, this is a message
for Colonel Mace from Jo, Jo Nakashima.

35
00:01:50,027 --> 00:01:52,029
Look, you should've got my e-mail.

36
00:01:52,195 --> 00:01:55,657
I've been investigating a number
of deaths related to Atmos systems.

37
00:01:55,741 --> 00:01:57,200
SATNAV: Go straight on.

38
00:01:57,284 --> 00:02:00,704
Now I can't prove anything,
but there's got to be a link.

39
00:02:00,787 --> 00:02:04,541
I need you to check out all the people
who died in Atmos cars yesterday.

40
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:07,628
-And then, check out the time.
-Turn right.

41
00:02:13,759 --> 00:02:17,137
-I don't believe this.
-This is your final destination.

42
00:02:17,220 --> 00:02:19,014
I said, take me to UNIT.

43
00:02:19,097 --> 00:02:20,182
(BEEPS)

44
00:02:20,265 --> 00:02:21,975
Go straight on.

45
00:02:22,059 --> 00:02:25,854
I don't think so.
I'll find my own way, thanks.

46
00:02:25,937 --> 00:02:27,606
(ENGINE REVVING)

47
00:02:29,733 --> 00:02:32,069
This is your final destination.

48
00:02:32,235 --> 00:02:34,863
-This is your final destination.
-No!

49
00:02:34,946 --> 00:02:37,741
-This is your final destination.
-No! Help!

50
00:02:37,866 --> 00:02:43,080
-This is your final destination.
-No, no, no! No!

51
00:02:51,338 --> 00:02:52,964
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

52
00:02:53,048 --> 00:02:56,551
-I can't believe I'm doing this.
-No. Neither can I.

53
00:02:57,010 --> 00:02:58,887
Whoa, whoa, careful.

54
00:03:01,807 --> 00:03:03,767
Left hand down. Left hand down.

55
00:03:05,644 --> 00:03:07,562
Getting a bit too close to the 1980s.

56
00:03:07,646 --> 00:03:09,356
What am I going to do?
Put a dent in them?

57
00:03:09,439 --> 00:03:10,565
Someone did.

58
00:03:10,649 --> 00:03:12,317
(MOBILE RINGING)

59
00:03:13,568 --> 00:03:14,820
Hold on.

60
00:03:15,320 --> 00:03:16,947
That's a phone.

61
00:03:19,616 --> 00:03:23,787
-You've got a mobile? Since when?
-It's not mine.

62
00:03:29,543 --> 00:03:30,794
Hello.

63
00:03:31,128 --> 00:03:33,255
Doctor, it's Martha.

64
00:03:34,172 --> 00:03:36,800
And I'm bringing you back to Earth.

65
00:03:36,967 --> 00:03:39,136
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

66
00:04:18,216 --> 00:04:21,553
(WHOOSHING)

67
00:04:31,229 --> 00:04:34,733
-Martha Jones.
-Doctor.

68
00:04:46,328 --> 00:04:48,955
-You haven't changed a bit.
-Neither have you.

69
00:04:49,039 --> 00:04:52,250
-How's the family?
-You know, not so bad. Recovering.

70
00:04:52,375 --> 00:04:53,919
What about you?

71
00:04:55,128 --> 00:04:58,048
Right. I should've known.

72
00:04:58,131 --> 00:04:59,883
Didn't take you long to replace me then.

73
00:04:59,966 --> 00:05:02,886
-Now, don't start fighting.
-Martha, Donna. Donna, Martha.

74
00:05:02,969 --> 00:05:04,763
Please don't fight.
I can't bear fighting.

75
00:05:04,846 --> 00:05:06,723
(CHUCKLING) You wish.

76
00:05:06,932 --> 00:05:09,059
I've heard all about you.
He talks about you all the time.

77
00:05:09,184 --> 00:05:10,811
-I dread to think.
-No, no, no.

78
00:05:10,894 --> 00:05:14,773
No. He says nice things, good things.
Nice things. Really good things.

79
00:05:14,898 --> 00:05:16,775
Oh, my God! He's told you everything.

80
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:18,777
Didn't take you long
to get over it, though.

81
00:05:18,860 --> 00:05:20,111
Who's the lucky man?

82
00:05:20,195 --> 00:05:23,323
-What man? The lucky what?
-She's engaged, you prawn.

83
00:05:23,406 --> 00:05:25,784
-Really? Who to?
-Tom. That Tom Milligan.

84
00:05:25,867 --> 00:05:27,077
He's in paediatrics.

85
00:05:27,202 --> 00:05:29,955
Working out in Africa right now,
and yes, I know,

86
00:05:30,038 --> 00:05:33,166
I've got a doctor who disappears off
to distant places. Tell me about it.

87
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:37,295
-Is he skinny?
-No. He's sort of strong.

88
00:05:37,379 --> 00:05:41,258
He is too skinny for words.
You give him a hug, you get a paper cut.

89
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:43,385
-Oh, I thought you were fighting.
-No. Speaking of which...

90
00:05:43,468 --> 00:05:45,679
WOMAN ON WALKIE-TALKIE:
Dr Jones, report to base, please. Over.

91
00:05:45,762 --> 00:05:49,140
This is Dr Jones.
Operation Blue Sky is go, go, go.

92
00:05:49,266 --> 00:05:51,309
I repeat, this is a go.

93
00:05:59,109 --> 00:06:02,362
SOLDIER: Unified Intelligence
Task Force. Raise that barrier now.

94
00:06:12,747 --> 00:06:16,251
Leave your safeties on, lads.
It's non-hostiles.

95
00:06:16,334 --> 00:06:19,796
OVER LOUDSPEAKER: All workers,
lay down your tools and surrender.

96
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:22,757
MARTHA: Greyhound 16 to Trap One,
B Section. Go, go, go!

97
00:06:22,841 --> 00:06:24,843
Search the ground floor.
Grid pattern Delta.

98
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:27,554
-What are you searching for?
-Illegal aliens.

99
00:06:27,637 --> 00:06:29,848
SOLDIER: 7his is a UNIT operation.

100
00:06:29,973 --> 00:06:35,437
All workers lay down your tools
and surrender immediately.

101
00:06:36,980 --> 00:06:38,398
B Section mobilised.

102
00:06:38,481 --> 00:06:41,359
E Section, F Section, on my command.

103
00:06:41,484 --> 00:06:45,113
Is that what you did to her?
Turned her into a soldier?

104
00:06:49,117 --> 00:06:53,204
SKORR: As predicted, the UNIT forces
have moved to the penultimate stage.

105
00:06:53,330 --> 00:06:54,998
STAAL: Observe their troops.

106
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:58,877
Thin fabrics, exposed skin,
feeble weapons.

107
00:06:59,002 --> 00:07:02,005
These are toy soldiers,
the playthings of children.

108
00:07:05,342 --> 00:07:09,220
-A Section, in position.
-We are on standby, sir.

109
00:07:10,180 --> 00:07:12,057
You're qualified now?
You're a proper doctor?

110
00:07:12,182 --> 00:07:14,434
UNIT rushed it through,
given my experience in the field.

111
00:07:14,517 --> 00:07:18,271
Here we go. We're establishing
a field base on site.

112
00:07:18,355 --> 00:07:22,067
-They're dying to meet you.
-Wish I could say the same.

113
00:07:25,445 --> 00:07:29,115
Operation Blue Sky complete, sir.
Thanks for letting me take the lead.

114
00:07:29,199 --> 00:07:31,493
And this is the Doctor.

115
00:07:32,661 --> 00:07:34,996
-Doctor, Colonel Mace.
-Sir.

116
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,540
-Oh, don't salute.
-But it's an honour, sir.

117
00:07:37,624 --> 00:07:38,875
I've read all the files on you.

118
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,211
Technically speaking,
you're still on staff.

119
00:07:41,294 --> 00:07:42,963
You never resigned.

120
00:07:43,046 --> 00:07:45,548
-What? You used to work for them?
-Yeah, a long time ago.

121
00:07:45,632 --> 00:07:47,342
Back in the '70s.

122
00:07:47,425 --> 00:07:50,971
Or was it the '80s? But it was all
a bit more homespun back then.

123
00:07:51,054 --> 00:07:54,307
-Times have changed, sir.
-Yeah, that's enough of the "sir".

124
00:07:54,391 --> 00:07:58,061
Come on now, Doctor. You've seen it.
You've been on board the Valiant.

125
00:07:58,144 --> 00:08:00,313
We've got massive funding
from the United Nations,

126
00:08:00,397 --> 00:08:04,234
-all in the name of Homeworld Security.
-A modern UNIT for the modern world.

127
00:08:04,401 --> 00:08:07,237
What, and that means arresting
ordinary factory workers,

128
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:09,239
in the streets in broad daylight?

129
00:08:09,322 --> 00:08:11,324
It's more like Guantanamo Bay out there.

130
00:08:11,408 --> 00:08:14,911
Donna. By the way, Donna Noble,
since you didn't ask.

131
00:08:15,328 --> 00:08:17,080
I'lLl have a salute.

132
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:22,293
-Ma'am.
-Thank you.

133
00:08:22,419 --> 00:08:24,879
So tell me,
what's going on in that factory?

134
00:08:24,963 --> 00:08:28,008
Yesterday, 52 people died
in identical circumstances,

135
00:08:28,091 --> 00:08:30,343
right across the world,
in 11 different time zones.

136
00:08:30,427 --> 00:08:31,511
(BEEPING)

137
00:08:31,594 --> 00:08:36,057
05:00 in the UK, 06:00 in France,
08:00 in Moscow, 13:00 in China...

138
00:08:36,141 --> 00:08:38,810
-You mean they died simultaneously?
-Exactly.

139
00:08:38,893 --> 00:08:42,063
52 deaths at the exact
same moment worldwide.

140
00:08:42,147 --> 00:08:44,607
-How did they die?
-They were all inside their cars.

141
00:08:44,691 --> 00:08:48,194
They were poisoned.
I checked the biopsies, no toxins.

142
00:08:48,278 --> 00:08:50,155
Whatever it is
left the system immediately.

143
00:08:50,238 --> 00:08:52,574
-What have the cars got in common?
-Completely different makes.

144
00:08:52,657 --> 00:08:55,285
They're all fitted with Atmos.
And that is the Atmos factory.

145
00:08:55,368 --> 00:08:57,954
-What is Atmos?
-Well, come on, even I know that.

146
00:08:58,038 --> 00:08:59,873
Everyone's got Atmos.

147
00:08:59,956 --> 00:09:02,459
It stands for
Atmospheric Omission System.

148
00:09:02,542 --> 00:09:05,545
The Atmos in your car
reduces CO2 emissions to zero.

149
00:09:05,628 --> 00:09:09,966
-Zero? No carbon, none at all?
-And you get Sat Nav thrown in,

150
00:09:10,050 --> 00:09:13,219
plus 20 quid in shopping vouchers
if you introduce a friend. Bargain.

151
00:09:13,303 --> 00:09:17,015
And this is where they make it, Doctor.
Shipping worldwide.

152
00:09:17,098 --> 00:09:20,310
17 factories across the globe,
but this is the central depot,

153
00:09:20,393 --> 00:09:22,437
sending Atmos to every country on Earth.

154
00:09:22,520 --> 00:09:24,272
And you think Atmos is alien?

155
00:09:24,355 --> 00:09:27,859
It's our job to investigate
that possibility. Doctor?

156
00:09:36,951 --> 00:09:38,912
And here it is, laid bare.

157
00:09:38,995 --> 00:09:42,499
Atmos can be threaded through
any and every make of car.

158
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:44,417
You must have checked it
before it went on sale.

159
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:46,252
We did. We found nothing.

160
00:09:46,336 --> 00:09:47,796
That's why I thought
we needed an expert.

161
00:09:47,879 --> 00:09:49,798
Really? Who'd you get?

162
00:09:52,509 --> 00:09:55,011
Oh, right! Me, yes. Good.

163
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:02,977
Okay, so why would aliens be so keen
on cleaning up our atmosphere?

164
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:04,938
A very good question.

165
00:10:05,021 --> 00:10:08,691
Maybe they want to help,
get rid of pollution and stuff.

166
00:10:09,692 --> 00:10:13,196
Do you know how many cars
there are on planet Earth?

167
00:10:13,404 --> 00:10:16,699
800 million. Imagine that.

168
00:10:18,660 --> 00:10:21,830
If you could control them,
you'd have 800 million weapons.

169
00:10:28,294 --> 00:10:31,172
We should head back.
There's not much down there.

170
00:10:31,256 --> 00:10:34,008
There should be just oil rooms,
generators.

171
00:10:38,555 --> 00:10:41,432
Aye, aye. What's this then?

172
00:10:46,354 --> 00:10:49,232
You two, all personnel
have been ordered to evacuate.

173
00:10:49,315 --> 00:10:50,733
Building's under UNIT control.

174
00:10:50,817 --> 00:10:54,154
-This area is out of bounds.
-Excuse me, sunshine?

175
00:10:56,406 --> 00:10:58,992
I think you'll find we're in charge.

176
00:11:00,869 --> 00:11:02,537
We can do this the easy way...

177
00:11:02,620 --> 00:11:03,663
(SNIFFING)

178
00:11:03,746 --> 00:11:05,081
...or the hard way.

179
00:11:05,206 --> 00:11:08,001
-SKORR: General Staal, they're close.
-STAAL: Excellent.

180
00:11:08,084 --> 00:11:11,880
And like a good warrior,
I shall enter the fray myself.

181
00:11:11,963 --> 00:11:13,548
Let them pass.

182
00:11:22,056 --> 00:11:23,433
It's open.

183
00:11:25,602 --> 00:11:26,936
Come on.

184
00:11:45,205 --> 00:11:46,748
What the hell?

185
00:11:50,501 --> 00:11:53,630
Greyhound 16 to Trap One.
We've found something.

186
00:11:54,297 --> 00:11:58,718
Basement corridor, north side, grid 36.
Request backup, over.

187
00:12:06,142 --> 00:12:08,811
It's like something boiling inside.

188
00:12:11,481 --> 00:12:14,442
-Well, don't touch it.
-Come on, Steve.

189
00:12:14,692 --> 00:12:16,986
We get first rights on this.

190
00:12:17,153 --> 00:12:19,989
-That means promotion.
-Just leave it alone.

191
00:12:20,114 --> 00:12:21,616
Wait for backup.

192
00:12:21,741 --> 00:12:23,076
(THUDDING)

193
00:12:23,493 --> 00:12:24,994
What was that?

194
00:12:26,329 --> 00:12:32,085
-It came from inside.
-It could just be the machinery.

195
00:12:32,168 --> 00:12:33,544
(THUDDING)

196
00:12:35,004 --> 00:12:36,506
(COCKS GUN)

197
00:12:40,718 --> 00:12:42,178
(THUDDING)

198
00:12:42,679 --> 00:12:45,431
Is there someone in there? Hello?

199
00:12:45,515 --> 00:12:47,600
(KNOCKING)

200
00:12:48,518 --> 00:12:50,019
We've got to get this open.

201
00:12:50,103 --> 00:12:54,148
-We should wait for the others.
-You could suffocate in there.

202
00:12:54,440 --> 00:12:56,025
Greyhound 16 to Trap One.

203
00:12:56,109 --> 00:12:59,279
Request immediate assistance.
Repeat, immediate assistance. Over.

204
00:12:59,362 --> 00:13:02,657
How do you work this thing? Come on.

205
00:13:05,493 --> 00:13:08,871
(ALARM BUZZING)

206
00:13:12,709 --> 00:13:14,127
(COUGHING)

207
00:13:15,461 --> 00:13:17,547
Oh, God! It stinks.

208
00:13:20,633 --> 00:13:22,885
What the hell is that stuff?

209
00:13:31,185 --> 00:13:33,896
Identify yourself. Identify.

210
00:13:35,773 --> 00:13:38,151
Greyhound 16
declaring absolute emergency, sir.

211
00:13:38,234 --> 00:13:40,778
Repeat, absolute emergency. Over.

212
00:13:40,987 --> 00:13:44,615
Can you hear me? Can you understand me?

213
00:13:46,868 --> 00:13:50,288
Look at his neck.
It's looks like an umbilical cord.

214
00:13:51,497 --> 00:13:55,084
-Well, don't get too close.
-I think it's harmless.

215
00:13:57,253 --> 00:13:59,839
I don't think it's properly alive.

216
00:14:01,549 --> 00:14:03,634
-It's going to drown.
-No.

217
00:14:04,927 --> 00:14:07,305
I think it breathes this stuff.

218
00:14:07,805 --> 00:14:11,601
-It's some kind of embryo.
-What do you mean, "an embryo"?

219
00:14:13,519 --> 00:14:18,274
Someone's growing a body. A human body.

220
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:21,110
Excellent skills of deduction.

221
00:14:21,235 --> 00:14:24,822
I would rate you above average, soldier.
Well done.

222
00:14:24,906 --> 00:14:28,451
Whereas you,
you smell of sweat and fear.

223
00:14:28,659 --> 00:14:29,869
Yeah?

224
00:14:30,953 --> 00:14:33,748
We're not the ones
who got out of school early, sonny.

225
00:14:33,831 --> 00:14:36,042
And stop playing Humpty Dumpty
and tell us who you are.

226
00:14:36,167 --> 00:14:38,669
Is that a reference to my height?

227
00:14:38,795 --> 00:14:41,714
-Short answer. Yes.
-A pity.

228
00:14:41,923 --> 00:14:45,718
Words are the weapons of womenfolk.
I must judge you unfit.

229
00:14:47,929 --> 00:14:50,681
What are you going to do?
Bite our ankles?

230
00:14:50,807 --> 00:14:52,141
(SCREAMS)

231
00:14:53,601 --> 00:14:56,896
-I'm warning you.
-A proper soldier gives no warning.

232
00:14:56,979 --> 00:14:59,899
Fire. I order you. Fire.

233
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:04,487
The room is contained within
a Cordolaine signal

234
00:15:04,570 --> 00:15:06,864
exciting the copper surface
of the bullet

235
00:15:06,989 --> 00:15:11,869
and causing expansion within the barrel,
rendering your guns useless.

236
00:15:12,662 --> 00:15:15,581
And your radio signals
have been blocked.

237
00:15:21,671 --> 00:15:24,173
My legs. I can't feel my legs.

238
00:15:24,257 --> 00:15:26,551
I apologise for disabling you.

239
00:15:27,009 --> 00:15:30,930
Death has more honour,
but you are needed for the stratagem.

240
00:15:31,931 --> 00:15:33,933
Prepare them for processing.

241
00:15:34,058 --> 00:15:38,438
You spoke of promotion,
now you will serve a greater cause.

242
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:43,443
-Who are you?
-Indeed. Know your enemy.

243
00:15:43,526 --> 00:15:47,029
I am General Staal
of the 10th Sontaran Battle Fleet,

244
00:15:47,113 --> 00:15:49,407
known as Staal the Undefeated.

245
00:15:55,037 --> 00:15:56,539
Oh, my God! Help us.

246
00:15:57,331 --> 00:16:00,460
Ionising nano-membrane
carbon dioxide converter,

247
00:16:00,543 --> 00:16:04,505
which means that Atmos works,
filters the CO2 at a molecular level.

248
00:16:04,589 --> 00:16:07,467
We know all that.
But what's its origin? Is it alien?

249
00:16:07,550 --> 00:16:09,427
No, but it's decades ahead of its time.

250
00:16:09,552 --> 00:16:11,471
Look, do you mind?
Could you stand back a bit?

251
00:16:11,554 --> 00:16:14,223
-Sorry. Have I done something wrong?
-You're carrying a gun.

252
00:16:14,348 --> 00:16:17,310
I don't like people with guns
hanging around me, all right?

253
00:16:17,393 --> 00:16:18,978
If you insist.

254
00:16:21,772 --> 00:16:23,065
Tetchy.

255
00:16:23,191 --> 00:16:25,735
-Well, it's true.
-He's a good man.

256
00:16:26,110 --> 00:16:29,655
People with guns are usually the enemy
in my books. You seem quite at home.

257
00:16:29,739 --> 00:16:31,616
If anyone got me used to fighting,
it's you.

258
00:16:31,741 --> 00:16:33,159
Oh, right. So it's my fault.

259
00:16:33,242 --> 00:16:36,412
Well, you got me the job.
Besides, look at me.

260
00:16:38,748 --> 00:16:41,417
-Am I carrying a gun?
-I suppose not.

261
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:43,503
It's all right for you.

262
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:47,298
You can just come and go,
but some of us have got to stay behind.

263
00:16:47,381 --> 00:16:49,342
So I've got to work from the inside.

264
00:16:49,425 --> 00:16:52,845
And by staying inside, maybe I stand
a chance of making them better.

265
00:16:52,929 --> 00:16:54,096
Yeah.

266
00:16:57,141 --> 00:16:59,018
That's more like Martha Jones.

267
00:16:59,101 --> 00:17:00,603
-I learnt from the best.
-Well...

268
00:17:00,728 --> 00:17:02,188
Oi, you lot.

269
00:17:02,355 --> 00:17:06,484
All your storm troopers and your sonics,
rubbish.

270
00:17:06,609 --> 00:17:08,653
-You should've come with me.
-Oh, where have you been?

271
00:17:08,736 --> 00:17:11,322
Personnel. That's where
the weird stuff's happening.

272
00:17:11,447 --> 00:17:14,617
In the paperwork.
'Cause I spent years working as a temp,

273
00:17:14,742 --> 00:17:16,619
I can find my way
around an office blindfold.

274
00:17:16,702 --> 00:17:19,664
And the first thing I noticed
is an empty file.

275
00:17:19,789 --> 00:17:22,542
Why, what's inside it?
Or what's not inside it?

276
00:17:22,625 --> 00:17:24,043
Sick days.

277
00:17:24,961 --> 00:17:29,215
There aren't any. Hundreds of people
working here and no one's sick.

278
00:17:29,298 --> 00:17:32,927
Not one hangover, man 'flu,
sneaky little shopping trip.

279
00:17:33,511 --> 00:17:36,305
Nothing. Not ever. They don't get ill.

280
00:17:37,181 --> 00:17:38,975
That can't be right.

281
00:17:39,809 --> 00:17:41,227
You've been checking out the building,

282
00:17:41,310 --> 00:17:43,312
you should've been checking out
the workforce.

283
00:17:43,396 --> 00:17:45,523
I can see why he likes you.

284
00:17:45,648 --> 00:17:48,317
-You are good.
-Super temp.

285
00:17:48,442 --> 00:17:51,445
Dr Jones, set up a medical post.
Start examining the workers.

286
00:17:51,529 --> 00:17:54,657
-I'll get them sent through.
-Come on, Donna. Give me a hand.

287
00:17:56,284 --> 00:17:59,287
So this Atmos thing,
where did it come from?

288
00:17:59,370 --> 00:18:02,039
-Luke Rattigan himself.
-That himself would be?

289
00:18:03,332 --> 00:18:04,917
A child genius.

290
00:18:05,167 --> 00:18:08,713
Invented the Fountain Six search engine
when he was 12 years old.

291
00:18:08,838 --> 00:18:12,341
Millionaire overnight.
Now runs the Rattigan Academy,

292
00:18:12,508 --> 00:18:16,178
a private school educating students
hand-picked from all over the world.

293
00:18:16,262 --> 00:18:19,056
A hothouse for geniuses.
I won't mind going there.

294
00:18:19,181 --> 00:18:20,683
I get lonely.

295
00:18:28,691 --> 00:18:32,612
Do you think I should warn my mum?
About the Atmos in her car.

296
00:18:32,695 --> 00:18:36,365
-Better safe than sorry.
-I'll give her a call.

297
00:18:36,490 --> 00:18:41,203
Donna, do they know where you are?
Your family?

298
00:18:41,287 --> 00:18:44,165
I mean, that you're travelling
with the Doctor?

299
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:48,210
Not really. Although my grandad
sort of waved us off.

300
00:18:48,419 --> 00:18:53,215
-But I didn't have time to explain.
-You just left him behind?

301
00:18:54,216 --> 00:18:55,384
Yeah.

302
00:18:57,219 --> 00:18:59,305
I didn't tell my family.

303
00:18:59,555 --> 00:19:03,434
I kept it all so secret.
It almost destroyed them.

304
00:19:03,726 --> 00:19:04,977
In what way?

305
00:19:05,061 --> 00:19:08,105
They ended up imprisoned.
They were tortured.

306
00:19:08,397 --> 00:19:11,192
My mum, my dad, my sister.

307
00:19:12,360 --> 00:19:16,072
It wasn't the Doctor's fault,
but you need to be careful.

308
00:19:16,906 --> 00:19:20,660
'Cause you know the Doctor.
He's wonderful, he's brilliant,

309
00:19:20,743 --> 00:19:22,536
but he's like fire.

310
00:19:25,039 --> 00:19:27,750
Stand too close and people get burnt.

311
00:19:35,341 --> 00:19:37,426
Conditioning is complete.

312
00:19:37,968 --> 00:19:41,597
Now do your duty
and advance the conquest.

313
00:19:42,598 --> 00:19:44,141
BOTH: Yes, sir.

314
00:19:49,897 --> 00:19:54,527
General Staal returning.
The stratagem advances.

315
00:19:57,780 --> 00:20:00,574
The last days of planet Earth.

316
00:20:00,658 --> 00:20:02,618
(OSCILLATING DRONE)

317
00:20:02,702 --> 00:20:04,120
You're not coming with me.

318
00:20:04,203 --> 00:20:06,914
I want to talk to this Luke Rattigan,
not point a gun at him.

319
00:20:06,997 --> 00:20:09,083
It's 10 miles outside London.
How are you going to get there?

320
00:20:09,166 --> 00:20:10,543
Well, then, get me a jeep.

321
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:12,795
According to the records,
you travel by Tardis.

322
00:20:12,878 --> 00:20:14,964
If there is a danger of hostile aliens,
I think it's best to keep

323
00:20:15,089 --> 00:20:17,007
a super-duper time machine
away from the front lines.

324
00:20:17,091 --> 00:20:20,052
I see, then you do have weapons,
but you choose to keep them hidden.

325
00:20:20,136 --> 00:20:21,470
-Jenkins.
-Sir.

326
00:20:21,637 --> 00:20:23,723
You will accompany the Doctor
and take orders from him.

327
00:20:23,806 --> 00:20:25,266
Yeah. I don't do orders.

328
00:20:25,349 --> 00:20:28,269
Any sign of trouble,
get Jenkins to declare a Code Red.

329
00:20:28,352 --> 00:20:30,438
-And good luck, sir.
-I said, "No salutes".

330
00:20:30,521 --> 00:20:32,732
Now you're giving orders.

331
00:20:32,815 --> 00:20:35,234
-Getting a bit cheeky, you are.
-Doctor.

332
00:20:35,317 --> 00:20:37,445
Oh, just in time. Come on.
Come on, we're going to the country.

333
00:20:37,528 --> 00:20:39,238
Fresh air and geniuses.
What more could you ask?

334
00:20:39,321 --> 00:20:41,365
I'm not coming with you.

335
00:20:42,199 --> 00:20:44,994
I've been thinking. I'm sorry.

336
00:20:46,078 --> 00:20:47,663
I'm going home.

337
00:20:48,706 --> 00:20:51,000
-Really?
-I've got to.

338
00:20:53,586 --> 00:20:56,505
Well, if that's what you want.

339
00:20:58,215 --> 00:20:59,884
I mean, it's a bit soon.

340
00:21:00,885 --> 00:21:03,846
I had so many places
I wanted to take you.

341
00:21:05,181 --> 00:21:08,184
The Fifteenth Broken Moon
of the Medusa Cascade.

342
00:21:08,350 --> 00:21:11,061
The lightning skies
of Cotter Palluni's world.

343
00:21:11,145 --> 00:21:15,357
The Diamond Coral Reefs
of Kataa Flo Ko.

344
00:21:19,987 --> 00:21:21,363
Thank you.

345
00:21:23,491 --> 00:21:26,535
Thank you, Donna Noble.
It's been brilliant. You've...

346
00:21:27,244 --> 00:21:29,872
You saved my life in so many ways.

347
00:21:31,749 --> 00:21:33,083
You're...

348
00:21:35,503 --> 00:21:38,047
You're just popping home for a visit,
that's what you mean.

349
00:21:38,214 --> 00:21:41,050
-You dumbo.
-And then you're coming back.

350
00:21:41,133 --> 00:21:45,971
Do you know what you are?
A great big outer-space dunce.

351
00:21:46,055 --> 00:21:48,432
-Yeah.
-Ready when you are, sir.

352
00:21:49,350 --> 00:21:52,436
What's more, you can give me a lift.
Come on.

353
00:21:53,437 --> 00:21:56,315
-Broken Moon of what?
-I know. I know.

354
00:22:02,112 --> 00:22:05,366
And your name's Treppa, yeah?
Is that Polish?

355
00:22:05,449 --> 00:22:08,077
Listen, we're not checking passports.
It's not about that, but...

356
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:10,204
Did you come across
from Poland just to work?

357
00:22:10,287 --> 00:22:12,748
-I came to do my job.
-Okay.

358
00:22:12,832 --> 00:22:15,793
I need to listen to your heartbeat.
This might be a bit cold.

359
00:22:15,876 --> 00:22:17,044
Lift.

360
00:22:20,381 --> 00:22:22,550
(HEART BEATING FAST)

361
00:22:28,556 --> 00:22:30,933
-Are you on any medication?
-I'm here to work.

362
00:22:31,100 --> 00:22:33,435
-How many hours a day do you work?
-24,

363
00:22:33,602 --> 00:22:35,604
You work 24 hours a day?

364
00:22:37,648 --> 00:22:38,858
Down.

365
00:22:40,109 --> 00:22:43,112
Mr Treppa, have you ever had
any form of hypnosis?

366
00:22:43,195 --> 00:22:45,739
-I'm here to work.
-Okay.

367
00:22:47,867 --> 00:22:49,827
If you could just wait here.

368
00:22:49,994 --> 00:22:51,912
MAN: Take those to the stores.

369
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:56,959
-Dr Jones.
-Not now. I'm busy.

370
00:22:57,042 --> 00:22:58,627
Just one question.

371
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:00,546
Do you have security clearance
level one?

372
00:23:00,629 --> 00:23:03,132
-Yes, I do. Why?
-Colonel Mace wants to see you.

373
00:23:03,215 --> 00:23:05,718
Oh, good, 'cause I want to see him.
Where is he?

374
00:23:05,801 --> 00:23:07,636
Come with us.

375
00:23:18,522 --> 00:23:21,650
DONNA: I'll walk the rest of the way.
I'll see you back at the factory, yeah?

376
00:23:21,734 --> 00:23:24,653
DOCTOR: Bye.
DONNA: And you be careful.

377
00:23:42,838 --> 00:23:46,759
-Haven't seen you for days.
-Been away.

378
00:23:56,518 --> 00:23:57,728
Help!

379
00:23:57,811 --> 00:23:59,897
-Hold on!
-I am!

380
00:24:21,794 --> 00:24:23,629
I'm waving at fat.

381
00:25:14,096 --> 00:25:16,181
What's he doing down here?

382
00:25:16,265 --> 00:25:19,476
-He asked to see you.
-Why? Has he found something?

383
00:25:37,995 --> 00:25:39,747
(MARTHA SCREAMING)

384
00:25:43,208 --> 00:25:46,795
I said so, didn't I?
Aliens! I said, they was real.

385
00:25:47,212 --> 00:25:50,132
I just didn't expect them
in a little blue box.

386
00:25:50,215 --> 00:25:52,885
-It's bigger on the inside.
-Yeah, but is it safe?

387
00:25:52,968 --> 00:25:55,554
This Doctor. Are you safe with him?

388
00:25:56,096 --> 00:26:00,893
He's amazing, gramps.
He's just dazzling.

389
00:26:01,477 --> 00:26:03,395
-And never tell him I said that.
-No.

390
00:26:03,479 --> 00:26:06,815
-But I trust him with my life.
-Hold up. I thought that was my job.

391
00:26:06,982 --> 00:26:08,233
You still come first.

392
00:26:08,317 --> 00:26:12,029
-For God's sake, don't tell your mother.
-I don't know.

393
00:26:12,654 --> 00:26:14,698
I mean, this is massive.

394
00:26:14,990 --> 00:26:17,534
It's sort of not fair
if she doesn't know.

395
00:26:17,659 --> 00:26:20,996
Doesn't know what?
And who's she? The cat's mother?

396
00:26:21,080 --> 00:26:23,373
And where have you been
these past few days, lady?

397
00:26:23,457 --> 00:26:26,001
After that silly little trick
with the car keys,

398
00:26:26,085 --> 00:26:28,670
I phoned Veena and she said
she hadn't seen hide nor hair.

399
00:26:28,754 --> 00:26:30,881
I've just been travelling.

400
00:26:30,964 --> 00:26:33,509
Oh, hark at her, Michael Palin.

401
00:26:33,592 --> 00:26:36,136
Are you staying for tea?
'Cause I haven't got anything in.

402
00:26:36,220 --> 00:26:39,098
I've been trying to keep your grandad
on that macrobiotic diet,

403
00:26:39,181 --> 00:26:42,059
but he sneaks off and gets pork pies
at the petrol station.

404
00:26:42,142 --> 00:26:44,686
Don't deny it.
I've seen the wrappers in the car.

405
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:46,563
Oh, I don't miss a trick.

406
00:26:46,647 --> 00:26:48,774
Now then,
what were you going to tell me?

407
00:26:48,857 --> 00:26:50,609
What don't I know?

408
00:26:53,570 --> 00:26:54,863
Nothing.

409
00:26:55,280 --> 00:26:58,283
-Just nothing.
-Good.

410
00:26:58,367 --> 00:27:00,994
Right, then. You can sit there
and cut out those coupons.

411
00:27:01,078 --> 00:27:02,454
Every penny helps.

412
00:27:02,538 --> 00:27:04,623
This new mortgage
doesn't pay for itself.

413
00:27:04,706 --> 00:27:07,209
-Dad, kettle on.
-Yeah. Kettle on.

414
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:12,464
UNIT's been watching
the Rattigan Academy for ages.

415
00:27:12,548 --> 00:27:14,216
It's all a bit Hitler Youth.

416
00:27:14,299 --> 00:27:16,635
Exercise at dawn
and classes and special diets.

417
00:27:16,718 --> 00:27:19,471
-SAT NAV: Turn left.
-Ross, one question.

418
00:27:19,555 --> 00:27:21,348
If UNIT think that Atmos is dodgy...

419
00:27:21,431 --> 00:27:24,476
How come we've got it in the jeeps?
Tell me about it.

420
00:27:24,560 --> 00:27:27,229
They're fitted as standard
on all government vehicles.

421
00:27:27,312 --> 00:27:29,815
We can't get rid of them till
we can prove there's something wrong.

422
00:27:29,898 --> 00:27:32,192
-Turn right.
-Drives me around the bend.

423
00:27:32,276 --> 00:27:34,403
-Oh, nice one.
-I timed that perfectly.

424
00:27:34,528 --> 00:27:36,238
Yeah. Yeah, you did.

425
00:27:37,739 --> 00:27:39,825
This is your final destination.

426
00:27:53,380 --> 00:27:57,593
Is it PE? Wouldn't mind a kick around.
I've got my daps on.

427
00:27:58,427 --> 00:28:00,095
-I suppose you're the Doctor.
-Hello.

428
00:28:00,179 --> 00:28:04,308
-Your Commanding Officer phoned ahead.
-Oh, I haven't got a Commanding Officer.

429
00:28:04,391 --> 00:28:05,726
Have you?

430
00:28:06,768 --> 00:28:09,229
-Oh, this is Ross. Say hello, Ross.
-Good afternoon, sir.

431
00:28:09,313 --> 00:28:12,482
Let's have a look, then.
I can smell genius...in a good way.

432
00:28:15,944 --> 00:28:17,988
Oh, now!

433
00:28:19,531 --> 00:28:21,408
That's clever, look.

434
00:28:22,034 --> 00:28:24,494
A single-molecule fabric.
How thin is that?

435
00:28:24,578 --> 00:28:28,624
You could pack a tent in a thimble.
Ooh! Gravity simulators.

436
00:28:30,876 --> 00:28:35,380
Terraforming, biospheres,
nano-tech steel construction.

437
00:28:35,881 --> 00:28:38,175
(CHUCKLES) This is brilliant.

438
00:28:38,258 --> 00:28:42,387
Do you know, with equipment like this
you could, ooh, I don't know,

439
00:28:42,471 --> 00:28:44,973
move to another planet or something?

440
00:28:45,057 --> 00:28:48,894
-If only that was possible.
-If only that were possible.

441
00:28:49,561 --> 00:28:51,313
Conditional clause.

442
00:28:53,440 --> 00:28:55,984
I think you'd better come with me.

443
00:28:57,986 --> 00:29:00,530
You're smarter than
the usual UNIT grunts.

444
00:29:00,614 --> 00:29:02,407
-I'll give you that.
-He called you a grunt.

445
00:29:02,491 --> 00:29:05,911
Don't call Ross a grunt. He's nice.
We like Ross. Look at this place.

446
00:29:05,994 --> 00:29:08,080
What exactly do you want?

447
00:29:08,163 --> 00:29:11,250
I was just thinking,
what a responsible 18 year old.

448
00:29:11,333 --> 00:29:13,543
Inventing zero-carbon cars.

449
00:29:14,544 --> 00:29:16,380
Saving the world.

450
00:29:17,005 --> 00:29:20,425
-It takes a man with vision.
-Hmm! Blinkered vision.

451
00:29:20,676 --> 00:29:22,010
'Cause Atmos means
more people driving.

452
00:29:22,094 --> 00:29:23,178
More cars, more petrol.

453
00:29:23,303 --> 00:29:25,305
End result, the oil's going
to run out faster than ever.

454
00:29:25,389 --> 00:29:27,015
The Atmos system
could make things worse.

455
00:29:27,099 --> 00:29:29,059
Yeah. Well, see, that's a tautology.

456
00:29:29,184 --> 00:29:30,435
You can't say Atmos system

457
00:29:30,519 --> 00:29:32,187
because it stands for
"Atmospheric Omission System".

458
00:29:32,312 --> 00:29:34,648
So you're saying Atmospheric Omission
System System.

459
00:29:34,731 --> 00:29:37,234
Do you see Mr Conditional Clause?

460
00:29:38,026 --> 00:29:41,863
It's been a long time since
anyone said no to you, isn't it?

461
00:29:42,489 --> 00:29:46,159
-I'm still right though.
-Not easy, is it? Being clever?

462
00:29:48,120 --> 00:29:50,789
You look at the world
and you connect things,

463
00:29:50,872 --> 00:29:54,543
random things, and think,
why can't anyone else see it?

464
00:29:55,210 --> 00:29:58,297
-The rest of the world is so slow.
-Yeah.

465
00:29:59,131 --> 00:30:01,675
-You're on your own.
-I know.

466
00:30:02,217 --> 00:30:05,637
But not with this. 'Cause there's no way
you invented this single-handedly.

467
00:30:05,721 --> 00:30:07,180
Might be Earth technology,
but that's like finding

468
00:30:07,306 --> 00:30:10,225
a mobile phone in the Middle Ages.
No. No. I'll tell you what it's like.

469
00:30:10,309 --> 00:30:13,478
It's like finding this
in the middle of someone's front room,

470
00:30:13,562 --> 00:30:15,230
albeit a very big front room.

471
00:30:15,314 --> 00:30:16,857
-Why, what is it?
-Nah!

472
00:30:16,940 --> 00:30:18,150
This looks like a thing, doesn't it?

473
00:30:18,233 --> 00:30:20,819
People don't question things.
You say, "It's a thing."

474
00:30:20,902 --> 00:30:23,322
-Leave it alone.
-Me, I make these connections,

475
00:30:23,405 --> 00:30:26,950
and this, to me,
looks like a teleport pod.

476
00:30:27,075 --> 00:30:28,118
(OSCILLATING DRONE)

477
00:30:30,370 --> 00:30:34,124
-TANNOY: Orbit now holding at 556. 3.
-Oh.

478
00:30:34,249 --> 00:30:36,543
Sector two, 7-0.

479
00:30:37,627 --> 00:30:39,087
We have an intruder.

480
00:30:39,171 --> 00:30:41,840
DOCTOR: How did he get in?
Intruder window?

481
00:30:41,923 --> 00:30:42,924
Bye, bye.

482
00:30:43,050 --> 00:30:44,801
(OSCILLATING DRONE)

483
00:30:44,885 --> 00:30:47,596
Ross, get out!
Luke, you'd better come with me.

484
00:30:50,849 --> 00:30:52,184
Sontaran!

485
00:30:53,018 --> 00:30:55,812
That's your name, isn't it?
You're a Sontaran.

486
00:30:55,937 --> 00:30:58,607
How did I know that, eh?
Fascinating, isn't it?

487
00:30:58,690 --> 00:31:00,108
Isn't that worth keeping me alive?

488
00:31:00,233 --> 00:31:02,944
I order you to surrender in the name
of the Unified Intelligence Task Force.

489
00:31:03,028 --> 00:31:05,947
That's not going to work.
Cordolaine signal, am I right?

490
00:31:06,031 --> 00:31:08,116
Copper excitations stopping the bullets.

491
00:31:08,200 --> 00:31:10,035
-How do you know so much?
-Well...

492
00:31:10,118 --> 00:31:12,079
-Who is he?
-He didn't give his name.

493
00:31:12,162 --> 00:31:15,999
Now this isn't typical
Sontaran behaviour, is it? Hiding.

494
00:31:16,166 --> 00:31:18,377
Using teenagers? Stopping bullets?

495
00:31:18,460 --> 00:31:21,797
A Sontaran should face bullets
with dignity. Shame on you.

496
00:31:21,880 --> 00:31:24,633
-You dish on our me, sir.
-Yeah? Then show yourself.

497
00:31:24,716 --> 00:31:27,803
I will look into my enemy's eyes.

498
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:40,315
-Oh, my God.
-And your name?

499
00:31:40,399 --> 00:31:43,735
General Staal,
of the 10th Sontaran Fleet.

500
00:31:43,819 --> 00:31:45,695
Staal the Undefeated.

501
00:31:45,779 --> 00:31:48,615
Oh, that's not a very good nickname.
What if you do get defeated?

502
00:31:48,698 --> 00:31:51,910
Staal the not-so-quite-undefeated
any more, but never mind?

503
00:31:51,993 --> 00:31:55,497
He looks like a potato, a baked potato,
a talking baked potato.

504
00:31:55,622 --> 00:31:59,209
Now, Ross, don't be rude.
You look like a pink weasel to him.

505
00:31:59,334 --> 00:32:02,754
The Sontarans are
the finest soldiers in the galaxy.

506
00:32:03,588 --> 00:32:05,841
Dedicated to a life of warfare.
A clone race.

507
00:32:05,924 --> 00:32:07,968
Grown in batches of millions
with only one weakness.

508
00:32:08,051 --> 00:32:11,012
-Sontarans have no weakness.
-No. It's a good weakness.

509
00:32:11,138 --> 00:32:13,723
Thought you were meant to be clever.
Only an idiot would provoke him.

510
00:32:13,807 --> 00:32:16,435
No, but the Sontarans are fed by
a Probic Vent in the back of their neck.

511
00:32:16,518 --> 00:32:18,770
That's their weak spot, which means

512
00:32:18,854 --> 00:32:22,107
they always have to face their enemies
in battle. Isn't that lovely?

513
00:32:22,190 --> 00:32:26,528
-They can never turn their back.
-We stare into the face of death.

514
00:32:26,611 --> 00:32:28,613
Yeah, well stare at this.

515
00:32:29,948 --> 00:32:32,033
(GENERAL STAAL SCREAMING)

516
00:32:33,285 --> 00:32:35,370
What have you done? What have you done?

517
00:32:48,008 --> 00:32:49,551
Don't touch me.

518
00:32:50,552 --> 00:32:54,556
A Sontaran would rather be
court-martial led than show pain.

519
00:32:55,390 --> 00:32:57,642
-I must return.
-But he broke the teleport.

520
00:32:57,726 --> 00:33:01,146
Ha! Primitive sonic trickery.

521
00:33:04,107 --> 00:33:06,276
The device is now repaired.

522
00:33:07,903 --> 00:33:09,696
(OSCILLATING DRONE)

523
00:33:11,239 --> 00:33:16,661
Our presence is known.
Soldiers, we move to a war footing.

524
00:33:16,870 --> 00:33:21,041
I see you faced battle open-skinned,
sir. Might I share that honour?

525
00:33:21,124 --> 00:33:22,959
-You may.
-Thank you.

526
00:33:28,465 --> 00:33:30,967
How do you tell each other apart?

527
00:33:33,136 --> 00:33:35,013
We say the same of humans.

528
00:33:35,096 --> 00:33:38,391
Tell me, boy, how many Atmos devices
have been installed?

529
00:33:38,475 --> 00:33:41,186
Ah! They've gone worldwide
with only about half.

530
00:33:41,269 --> 00:33:46,274
Which means 400 million cars converted.
A fine arsenal.

531
00:33:46,399 --> 00:33:48,026
Is it sufficient
to trigger the conversion?

532
00:33:48,109 --> 00:33:51,238
More than enough, yeah. And
the test signal proved that it works.

533
00:33:51,321 --> 00:33:55,367
52 deaths in the same second, man.
That is just so cool.

534
00:33:55,450 --> 00:33:57,827
Is the temperature significant?

535
00:34:00,705 --> 00:34:03,375
No. That's just a phrase.

536
00:34:05,335 --> 00:34:08,129
But I'll get my people ready, General.
Just tell me where and when.

537
00:34:08,213 --> 00:34:11,174
-Have we infiltrated UNIT?
-The process is about to begin.

538
00:34:11,258 --> 00:34:14,636
Then you'll see it completed,
Commander Skorr.

539
00:34:14,761 --> 00:34:16,638
-Get to it.
-Yes, sir.

540
00:34:27,190 --> 00:34:30,777
Is someone going to tell me
what the hell is going on?

541
00:34:32,654 --> 00:34:33,863
Okay.

542
00:34:36,199 --> 00:34:37,826
So, listen.

543
00:34:38,034 --> 00:34:41,705
You're not the first aliens I've met.
Just tell me who you are.

544
00:34:41,830 --> 00:34:45,250
Commander Skorr of
the 10th Sontaran Battle Fleet,

545
00:34:45,333 --> 00:34:49,754
-known as Skorr, the Blood Bringer.
-What have you done to those two?

546
00:34:49,838 --> 00:34:52,924
Simple hypnotic control,
as with the factory drones.

547
00:34:53,008 --> 00:34:56,636
But with you,
we need something more complex.

548
00:34:58,179 --> 00:34:59,889
(MACHINE BUZZING)

549
00:35:06,396 --> 00:35:08,315
What is that?

550
00:35:08,398 --> 00:35:11,526
Soon, that will be you.

551
00:35:18,033 --> 00:35:21,411
(INDISTINCT SPEAKING ON PA SYSTEM)

552
00:35:28,543 --> 00:35:29,878
Continue.

553
00:35:44,976 --> 00:35:47,228
War can never come too soon.

554
00:35:48,355 --> 00:35:50,440
Take your last look, boy.

555
00:35:52,984 --> 00:35:55,320
It was never big enough for me.

556
00:35:55,403 --> 00:35:57,238
I like your ambition.

557
00:36:00,200 --> 00:36:04,245
That Doctor, he was in a UNIT jeep.
It should have Atmos installed.

558
00:36:04,329 --> 00:36:06,873
You said you didn't know his name.

559
00:36:07,916 --> 00:36:11,711
I don't. He just said Doctor.
Does that mean something?

560
00:36:11,795 --> 00:36:15,715
There is an enemy of the Sontarans
known as the Doctor.

561
00:36:16,174 --> 00:36:19,511
-A face changer.
-Do you mean he is an alien, too?

562
00:36:19,594 --> 00:36:23,348
Legend says he led the battle
in the last great Time War.

563
00:36:23,932 --> 00:36:27,602
The finest war in history
and we weren't allowed to be part of it.

564
00:36:27,727 --> 00:36:30,105
Oh, but this is excellent.

565
00:36:30,730 --> 00:36:36,361
The last of the Time Lords will die
at the hands of the Sontaran Empire

566
00:36:36,444 --> 00:36:40,615
in the ruins of his precious Earth.

567
00:37:00,468 --> 00:37:04,389
It is inadvisable to struggle.
The female has a weak thorax.

568
00:37:04,472 --> 00:37:07,142
-But what are you doing?
-Completing mental transfer.

569
00:37:07,267 --> 00:37:10,520
-The clone needs full memory access.
-Clone?

570
00:37:20,530 --> 00:37:22,365
No, you can't.

571
00:37:27,620 --> 00:37:30,165
-That's not...
-You'll sleep, girl.

572
00:37:30,874 --> 00:37:33,626
Sleep and keep the memories alive.

573
00:37:34,294 --> 00:37:37,255
Memories we can use in battle.

574
00:37:38,089 --> 00:37:40,175
SKREE: We have the Doctor's vehicle.

575
00:37:40,258 --> 00:37:43,636
An ordinary death
for such a remarkable enemy.

576
00:37:43,720 --> 00:37:45,013
But proceed.

577
00:37:46,931 --> 00:37:50,560
Greyhound 40 to Trap One.
Repeat. Can you hear me? Over.

578
00:37:51,186 --> 00:37:53,021
-Why is it not working?
-Must be the Sontarans.

579
00:37:53,104 --> 00:37:55,231
If they can trace that,
they can isolate the Atmos.

580
00:37:55,356 --> 00:37:56,983
-SAT NAN: Turn left.
-Try going right.

581
00:37:57,066 --> 00:37:59,652
-It said left.
-I know, so go right.

582
00:38:00,487 --> 00:38:02,739
I've got no control.
It's driving itself.

583
00:38:02,822 --> 00:38:05,450
It won't stop. The doors are locked.

584
00:38:05,533 --> 00:38:07,202
Aah! It's deadlocked. I can't stop it.

585
00:38:07,327 --> 00:38:09,120
-Let me...
-Turn left.

586
00:38:09,204 --> 00:38:11,956
The sat nav's just a box.
It's wired into the whole car.

587
00:38:12,040 --> 00:38:16,044
Is he going in the water?
I love it when they hit the water.

588
00:38:16,753 --> 00:38:19,005
We're heading for the river.

589
00:38:21,007 --> 00:38:23,134
Atmos, are you programmed
to contradict my orders?

590
00:38:23,218 --> 00:38:25,178
-Confirmed.
-Anything I say, you'll ignore it.

591
00:38:25,261 --> 00:38:26,721
Confirmed.

592
00:38:26,805 --> 00:38:30,016
Then drive into the river.
I order you to drive me into the river.

593
00:38:30,099 --> 00:38:31,893
Do it. Drive into the river.

594
00:38:42,111 --> 00:38:43,988
Turn right. Left.

595
00:38:44,072 --> 00:38:48,743
-Get down.
-Left, right, left right...

596
00:38:52,956 --> 00:38:54,249
Oh, is that it?

597
00:38:55,625 --> 00:39:00,255
Atmos terminated. Mission accomplished.
The Doctor is dead.

598
00:39:00,839 --> 00:39:02,924
Then prepare the weapons.

599
00:39:03,424 --> 00:39:05,510
Is the operative in place?

600
00:39:14,769 --> 00:39:17,689
Ready and waiting to advance
the great Sontaran cause, sir.

601
00:39:17,772 --> 00:39:19,440
Then go to work.

602
00:39:22,944 --> 00:39:24,487
(BELL RINGING)

603
00:39:28,283 --> 00:39:31,202
You would not believe
the day I'm having.

604
00:39:43,298 --> 00:39:45,717
-I'll requisition us a vehicle.
-Anything without Atmos.

605
00:39:45,800 --> 00:39:47,385
And don't point your gun at people.

606
00:39:47,468 --> 00:39:51,806
Is it him? Is it him? Is it the Doctor?

607
00:39:53,308 --> 00:39:57,186
-Oh, it's you.
-Who? Oh!

608
00:39:59,022 --> 00:40:00,356
It's you.

609
00:40:01,316 --> 00:40:03,401
-What, have you met before?
-Yeah. Christmas Eve.

610
00:40:03,484 --> 00:40:05,904
He disappeared right in front of me.

611
00:40:05,987 --> 00:40:08,698
-And you never said.
-Well, you never said.

612
00:40:08,781 --> 00:40:12,452
Wilf, sir. Wilfred Mott.
You must be one of them aliens.

613
00:40:12,660 --> 00:40:16,247
Yeah, but don't shout it out.
Nice to meet you properly, Wilf.

614
00:40:16,331 --> 00:40:18,875
-Ah, an alien hand.
-Donna, anything?

615
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:21,336
She's not answering.
What is it, Sonterruns?

616
00:40:21,419 --> 00:40:23,379
Sontarans.
But there's got to be more to it.

617
00:40:23,463 --> 00:40:26,090
They can't just be remote-controlling
cars. That's not enough.

618
00:40:26,174 --> 00:40:27,884
-Is anyone answering?
-Hold on.

619
00:40:28,009 --> 00:40:31,721
-Don't tell me. Donna Noble.
-Martha. Hold on, he's here.

620
00:40:32,513 --> 00:40:35,183
Martha, tell Colonel Mace
it's the Sontarans.

621
00:40:35,266 --> 00:40:36,935
They're in the file. Code Red Sontarans.

622
00:40:37,018 --> 00:40:39,312
But if they're inside the factory,
tell him not to start shooting.

623
00:40:39,437 --> 00:40:41,230
UNIT will get massacred.

624
00:40:41,356 --> 00:40:43,107
I'll get back as soon as I can.
You got that?

625
00:40:43,191 --> 00:40:45,360
Code Red Sontaran. Gotcha.

626
00:40:45,568 --> 00:40:50,573
-Dr Jones, found anything yet?
-No, sir. Nothing to report.

627
00:40:54,827 --> 00:40:56,913
You tried sonicking it before
and you didn't find anything.

628
00:40:56,996 --> 00:40:59,582
Yeah, but now I know it's Sontaran,
I know what I'm looking for.

629
00:40:59,666 --> 00:41:02,627
The thing is, Doctor,
that Donna is my only grandchild.

630
00:41:02,710 --> 00:41:04,712
You got to promise me
you're going to take care of her.

631
00:41:04,796 --> 00:41:08,007
-She takes care of me.
-Oh, yeah. That's my Donna.

632
00:41:08,091 --> 00:41:10,760
She was always bossing us around
even when she was tiny.

633
00:41:10,843 --> 00:41:12,220
The Little General we used to call her.

634
00:41:12,303 --> 00:41:13,930
-Yeah. Don't start.
-And some of the boys

635
00:41:14,013 --> 00:41:16,224
she used to turn up with,
a different one every week.

636
00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:18,810
Here. Who was that one
with the nail varnish?

637
00:41:18,893 --> 00:41:22,730
Matthew Richards.
He lives in Kilburn now...with a man.

638
00:41:23,773 --> 00:41:26,442
Whoa! It's a temporal pocket.

639
00:41:26,567 --> 00:41:28,778
I knew there was
something else in there.

640
00:41:28,903 --> 00:41:31,280
It's hidden just a second
out of sync with real time.

641
00:41:31,364 --> 00:41:35,576
-But what's it hiding?
-I don't know. Men and their cars.

642
00:41:35,702 --> 00:41:38,204
Sometimes I think if I was a car...

643
00:41:38,788 --> 00:41:42,458
-Oh, it's you. Doctor, what was it?
-Yeah, that's me.

644
00:41:42,583 --> 00:41:46,295
-What, have you met him as well?
-Dad, it's the man from the wedding

645
00:41:46,421 --> 00:41:49,382
when you were laid up with Spanish 'flu.

646
00:41:49,465 --> 00:41:52,844
I'm warning you. Last time that man
turned up, it was a disaster.

647
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:55,346
Get back.

648
00:41:55,430 --> 00:41:58,474
-A converter has been activated.
-Show me where.

649
00:41:58,558 --> 00:42:00,143
(DRONING)

650
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:02,645
London. That's Chiswick.

651
00:42:02,729 --> 00:42:05,606
-Who can have such knowledge?
-Only the Doctor.

652
00:42:05,773 --> 00:42:09,652
He survived. Excellent.
Then battle will be joined.

653
00:42:10,194 --> 00:42:13,990
Glorious warfare.
Tenth Sontaran Battle Fleet.

654
00:42:14,073 --> 00:42:18,494
We move to the final phase.
Prepare the subjugation of Earth

655
00:42:18,619 --> 00:42:20,621
for the glory of Sontar.

656
00:42:21,122 --> 00:42:23,332
VOICE ON PA:
Announcing Battle Status One.

657
00:42:23,458 --> 00:42:25,251
All soldiers to positions.

658
00:42:25,376 --> 00:42:29,714
Repeat, we are now at Battle Status One.
Rejoice.

659
00:42:42,685 --> 00:42:44,562
That'll stop it.

660
00:42:45,063 --> 00:42:48,733
I told you. He's blown up the car.

661
00:42:48,816 --> 00:42:52,153
Who is he anyway?
What sort of Doctor blows up cars?

662
00:42:52,236 --> 00:42:55,740
-Oh, not now, Mum.
-Oh, should I make an appointment?

663
00:42:55,907 --> 00:43:00,661
That wasn't just exhaust fumes.
It's some sort of gas, artificial gas.

664
00:43:00,745 --> 00:43:05,083
-And it's aliens. Is it aliens?
-Is this poisonous?

665
00:43:06,834 --> 00:43:09,504
Then they've got poisonous gas
in every car on Earth.

666
00:43:12,006 --> 00:43:16,010
Trigger the converters
and deadlock every single one.

667
00:43:16,135 --> 00:43:18,471
It's not safe.
I'm going to get it off the street.

668
00:43:20,264 --> 00:43:21,349
No, don't.

669
00:43:21,432 --> 00:43:23,351
(CAR ENGINE STARTING)

670
00:43:23,851 --> 00:43:25,436
Turn it off.

671
00:43:25,895 --> 00:43:29,107
-Grandad, get out of there.
-I can't. It's locked.

672
00:43:29,190 --> 00:43:31,192
It's them aliens again.

673
00:43:31,651 --> 00:43:33,027
(CAR HONKS)

674
00:43:33,111 --> 00:43:34,529
What's he doing? What's he doing?

675
00:43:34,654 --> 00:43:36,364
They've isolated it.

676
00:43:38,491 --> 00:43:40,368
(CAR ALARMS SOUNDING)

677
00:43:50,670 --> 00:43:53,339
Turn them off. Turn them off.

678
00:43:55,133 --> 00:43:57,510
-MACE: Turn off the engines.
-SOLDIER: It's all of them, sir.

679
00:43:57,593 --> 00:43:59,971
Every single car on the planet.

680
00:44:03,641 --> 00:44:06,352
Now we begin. Let's get to work.

681
00:44:10,231 --> 00:44:15,111
There's gas inside the car.
He's going to choke. Doctor!

682
00:44:17,321 --> 00:44:18,906
It won't open.

683
00:44:19,615 --> 00:44:21,242
(CARS HONKING)

684
00:44:21,742 --> 00:44:23,619
It's the whole world.

685
00:44:31,669 --> 00:44:36,591
400 million weapons. Sontar-ha!

686
00:44:36,674 --> 00:44:39,969
-(CHANTING) Sontar-ha!
-ALL: (CHANTING) Sontar-ha!

687
00:44:50,271 --> 00:44:52,190
(COUGHING AND CHOKING)

688
00:44:54,942 --> 00:44:56,235
Donna!

689
00:45:02,950 --> 00:45:05,203
ALL: (CHANTING) Sontar-ha!

690
00:45:15,630 --> 00:45:17,006
DONNA: Doctor!

691
00:45:49,830 --> 00:45:52,041
The government has declared
a state of emergency.

692
00:45:52,124 --> 00:45:53,584
WOMAN: Launching in 10.

693
00:45:53,668 --> 00:45:54,752
Come then.

694
00:45:54,835 --> 00:45:55,878
Nine.

695
00:45:55,962 --> 00:45:58,464
-Do not engage the Sontarans in battle.
-Eight.

696
00:45:58,547 --> 00:46:01,467
-The planet is going nuclear.
-Seven.

697
00:46:01,550 --> 00:46:03,678
It's time I reveal
what our work has been for.

698
00:46:03,761 --> 00:46:05,763
-Six.
-The bravery of idiots

699
00:46:05,846 --> 00:46:08,641
-is bravery, nonetheless.
-Five.

700
00:46:08,724 --> 00:46:10,851
-God save us.
-Four.

701
00:46:10,977 --> 00:46:12,645
They need this gas for something else.

702
00:46:12,728 --> 00:46:14,730
-Three.
-All troops, Code Red.

703
00:46:14,855 --> 00:46:16,774
-Two.
-At arms.

704
00:46:16,857 --> 00:46:19,110
-One.
-Get them out of there!

705
00:46:19,193 --> 00:46:20,569
Zero.

